> Kothu is a popular Sri Lankan street food dish which typically stir-fries meat and vegetables with chopped up pieces of roti. Here, we've made it even simpler by using tortilla pieces instead of roti - you'll be surprised how close they come to the real thing!

== Cooking the Beef ==

Heat a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%grams} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

While the beef fries, trim the @carrot{1} and coarsely grate (no need to peel).

Pile the @plain taco tortillas{6} onto each other and slice the tortillas into 1cm thick strips. Cut the strips into smaller approximately 3cm long strips (use #scissors{} if easier).

== Making the Kothu ==

When the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Stir in the @korma curry paste{50%grams}, @Sri Lankan style curry powder{1%sachet} and @ginger, garlic & lemongrass puree{15%grams}. Fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @kale{100%grams}(chopped) along with the @water{2%tbsp} and cook until starting to wilt, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the carrot, tortilla strips and @sugar{1%tsp}.

Stir-fry, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Next, stir in the @creme fraiche{75%grams}, @honey{1%tbsp} and @water{75%milliliters}. Simmer until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share the Sri Lankan style kothu between your #serving bowls{}.

Enjoy!